1. OSI Model:

There are 7 layers:
Application, Presentation, Session, Transport, Network, Data Link, Physical.
Example protocols:
Application - HTTP
Presentation - SSL
Session - NetBIOS
Transport - TCP
Network - IP
Data Link - Ethernet
Physical - Cables
TCP works at Transport layer.

2.IP Addressing

Public vs. Private IP: A Public IP is used to identify devices across the entire internet and is unique worldwide. A Private IP is used within a local network (like your home or office) and is not routable on the public internet.
Private IP Ranges:
Class A: 10.0.0.0 – 10.255.255.255
Class B: 172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255
Class C: 192.168.0.0 – 192.168.255.255
Classification: 192.168.1.100 is a Private IP address.

3.Protocols

Port Matching:
22: SSH (Secure Shell)
80: HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol)
443: HTTPS (HTTP Secure)
3306: MySQL Database


TCP vs. UDP: 
TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) is connection-oriented, meaning it ensures all data packets arrive in order and without errors. UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is connectionless and faster but does not guarantee delivery or order.


NAT (Network Address Translation):
NAT allows multiple devices on a private network to share a single public IP address. It is needed to conserve the limited supply of IPv4 addresses and to provide a layer of security by hiding internal IP addresses from the public internet.